#### 1. **Singleton Pattern for Hardware Modules**
The system uses a singleton pattern to manage hardware resources like `Application`, `Board`, and others. This ensures only one instance of critical hardware abstractions exists throughout the program lifecycle.
```cpp
#define DECLARE_BOARD(BOARD_IMPL) \
    static Board* CreateBoard() { return new BOARD_IMPL(); } \
    static Board* GetInstance() { \
        static Board* board = CreateBoard(); \
        return board; \
    }
```

#### 2. **I2C Device Initialization (XL9555 Example)**
Used for initializing external I/O expanders over I2C. The example shows how registers are written to configure pin directions and states:
```cpp
class XL9555 : public I2cDevice {
public:
    XL9555(i2c_master_bus_handle_t i2c_bus, uint8_t addr) : I2cDevice(i2c_bus, addr) {
        WriteReg(0x06, 0x03); // Configure Port 0 direction
        WriteReg(0x07, 0xF0); // Configure Port 1 direction
    }

    void SetOutputState(uint8_t bit, uint8_t level) {
        uint16_t data;
        int index = bit;

        if (bit < 8) {
            data = ReadReg(0x02);
        } else {
            data = ReadReg(0x03);
            index -= 8;
        }

        data = (data & ~(1 << index)) | (level << index);

        if (bit < 8) {
            WriteReg(0x02, data);
        } else {
            WriteReg(0x03, data);
        }
    }
};
```

